()Wrapper call aur Core engine call me antar kya?
--1️⃣ Core Engine Call
Definition:-
Core engine call matlab directly SailPoint ka backend engine use karna. Ye wo logic hai jo system ke andar kaam karta hai, jaise workflow run karna, task execute karna, identity create/update karna.

Characteristics:-
()Direct execution: Ye directly engine ke methods ko call karta hai.
()Low-level operations: Database operations, transactions, state changes sab directly engine handle karta hai.
()No abstraction: Developer ko khud hi input validation, error handling aur logging handle karna padta hai.
()Advanced users ke liye: Mainly internal modules aur custom code me use hota hai.
()Powerful but risky: Agar galat input de do to exception ya system crash ho sakta hai.

Example (Workflow launch using core engine):-
// Core engine call example
SailPointContext context = new SailPointContext();
Workflow workflow = workflowService.getWorkflow("UserOnboarding");
Attributes args = new Attributes();
args.put("identityName", "jokerboy");

WorkflowCase wfCase = workflowService.launchWorkflow(workflow, args);
// Direct engine call, returns WorkflowCase

Yahan kya ho raha hai:-
workflowService.getWorkflow() = Core engine se workflow definition fetch kiya
launchWorkflow() = Directly engine ke andar workflow execute kiya
Developer ko khud ensure karna hoga ki args valid ho aur exceptions handle ho.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2️⃣ Wrapper Call:-
Definition:-
Wrapper call ek high-level interface hai jo core engine calls ke upar banta hai. Matlab ye core engine ko internally call karta hai,
lekin extra safety aur convenience provide karta hai.

Characteristics:-
()Abstraction layer: Complex engine calls simple interface ke through accessible hote hai.
()Built-in validation: Arguments check ho jate hai, errors handle ho jate hai.
()Logging and notifications: Engine call ke sath extra functionality include hoti hai.
()Safe and easy: Mostly UI, API, aur integration modules me use hota hai.
()Less control than core engine: Agar deep customization chahiye, to wrapper limited ho sakta hai.

Example (Workflow launch using wrapper):-

// Wrapper call example
WorkflowHelper workflowHelper = new WorkflowHelper(context);
Map<String, Object> args = new HashMap<>();
args.put("identityName", "jokerboy");

// Wrapper internally core engine call karta hai
WorkflowCase wfCase = workflowHelper.launch("UserOnboarding", args);

Yahan kya ho raha hai:-
workflowHelper.launch() = ek wrapper method
Internally ye workflowService.launchWorkflow() (core engine) ko call karta hai,
Wrapper ne argument validation, logging, aur post-processing handle kar diya,
Developer ko sirf workflow name aur arguments provide karne hote hai.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
()Wrapper vs Core:-
Wrapper call (custom project)
wfService.resumeWorkflow(String workflowCaseId);
wfService.resumeWorkflow(WorkflowCase workflowCase);

()Core engine call:-
wfService.resume(WorkflowCase workflowCase);
wfService.resume(String workflowCaseId); // internally fetch + resume
